# Internationalization (i18n) and RTL Rules

## Overview
Rules for implementing bilingual support (English/Arabic) with RTL layout.

## Rules

### Always Add Translation Keys
- Always add new message keys into `en.json` and `ar.json`
- Never hardcode user-facing strings
- Use translation keys consistently throughout the app

### Backend Strategy
- Store EN/AR fields in database: `name`/`name2`, `description`/`description2`
- Return both languages in API responses
- Use bilingual field pattern for all user-facing text

### Frontend Setup (Next.js)
- Use next-intl provider and locale-aware `<html dir>` attribute
- Use Tailwind RTL utilities for spacing, alignment, and icon direction
- Test Arabic screens, forms, tables, and navigation

### Languages Supported
- English (en) - Default
- Arabic (ar) - RTL support required

### RTL Support
- Set `dir="rtl"` on HTML element when locale is Arabic
- Use Tailwind RTL classes: `rtl:text-right`, `rtl:ml-0 rtl:mr-4`
- Flip icons automatically: `rtl:rotate-180`
- Use direction-aware spacing and alignment

### Date & Time Formatting
- Use locale-aware date formatting: `ar-OM` for Arabic, `en-OM` for English
- Use locale-aware currency formatting: `ar-OM` for Arabic, `en-OM` for English
- Format according to user locale preference

### Font Setup
- Import Noto Sans Arabic font for Arabic text
- Apply Arabic font when `dir="rtl"`

### Testing Checklist
- All text aligns correctly in Arabic
- Forms flow right-to-left
- Tables display correctly
- Navigation menus appear on correct side
- Icons face correct direction
- Modals and dropdowns position correctly
- Charts and graphs display properly
- Print layouts work in both directions

## Conventions
- Always use translation keys, never hardcode strings
- Always test RTL layout for Arabic interface
- Always include both English and Arabic fields in database
- Always format dates and currency according to locale
